article.description: Nicole Powell scored a season-high 21 points, including the go-ahead basket, and the Sacramento Monarchs held off the Minnesota Lynx 85-80 on Friday night.
article.headline: Powell's bank shot clinches 11th straight win against Lynx
article.linkText: Powell's jumper clinches 11th straight win vs. Lynx
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS -- The Sacramento Monarchs showed more poise
down the stretch than the Lynx on Friday night, and the result was
an 11th consecutive victory over Minnesota.

	   Nicole Powell scored a season-high 21 points, including the
go-ahead basket late in the fourth quarter, and the Monarchs held
off the Lynx 85-80 at Williams Arena.

	   The game was played on the University of Minnesota campus
because the Target Center -- the Lynx's usual home building -- was
undergoing preparations for Prince's concert Saturday night.

	   It was the first regular-season home game in Lynx history not
played at the Target Center.

	   Rebekkah Brunson added 10 points and seven rebounds for
Sacramento, which hasn't lost to Minnesota since an 83-73 overtime
defeat July 11, 2004, at Target Center.

	   The Monarchs, the WNBA runners-up last season and WNBA champions
in 2005, improved their Western Conference-leading record to 12-6.

	   "I think when you have a young team, sometimes, you lose your
composure," said Lynx second-year guard Seimone Augustus, who
scored 23 points. "It's something we're going to have to work on
if we're going to get to a Sacramento level, a Detroit level, an
Indiana Fever level."

	   Nicole Ohlde had 21 points and eight rebounds for Minnesota,
which lost its second game in less than a week to Sacramento. The
Monarchs beat the Lynx 76-68 on Sunday in Sacramento.

	   Svetlana Abrosimova added 10 points and seven rebounds for
Minnesota, which has lost three consecutive games and is 0-3
against Sacramento this season.

	   "We did a lot of things better tonight," Lynx coach Don
Zierden said. "We had more assists than turnovers, we outrebounded
them. It just came down to shooting percentage."

	   Sacramento shot 58.9 percent from the field and held Minnesota
to 43.8 percent.

	   Still, the Lynx had a chance to win this one.

	   The Monarchs, up 43-38 at halftime, went on an 18-10 run to
start the third quarter and took a 61-48 lead on Scholanda
Robinson's turnaround jumper with 2:40 left in the third.

	   Kristin Haynie's short jumper gave Sacramento a 68-57 advantage
with 7:34 remaining in the fourth, but Minnesota rallied.

	   Augustus' baseline floater tied the score at 76 with 1:45 left.
Powell, who hit a 3-pointer to put the Monarchs ahead 76-74,
responded with a 10-foot bank shot with 1:21 remaining to give
Sacramento the lead for good at 78-76.

	   "Nicole Powell is a heck of a player," Zierden said.

	   Ticha Penicheiro made a jumper to put the Monarchs up 80-76 with
39 seconds left, and Sacramento went 5-for-6 from the free-throw
line late to seal the victory.

	   The Lynx (5-13) have lost two straight home games after winning
three in a row.
